mcvis: compare python and R

Kevin Wang

06/08/2019

library(mcvis)
library(tidyverse)
## ── Attaching packages ───────────────────────────────── tidyverse 1.2.1 ──
## ✔ ggplot2 3.2.0     ✔ purrr   0.3.2
## ✔ tibble  2.1.3     ✔ dplyr   0.8.3
## ✔ tidyr   0.8.3     ✔ stringr 1.4.0
## ✔ readr   1.3.1     ✔ forcats 0.4.0
## ── Conflicts ──────────────────────────────────── tidyverse_conflicts() ──
## ✖ dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## ✖ dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
set.seed(1)
p = 10
n = 1000
X = matrix(rnorm(n*p), ncol = p)
X[,1] = X[,2] + rnorm(n, 0, 0.1)

R compute and plotting

r_result = mcvis(X)
ggplot_mcvis(r_result)

Python compute and plotting

library(reticulate)
use_python("/usr/local/bin/python3", required = TRUE)
Sys.setenv(RETICULATE_PYTHON = "/usr/local/bin/python3")
reticulate::py_config()
## python:         /usr/local/bin/python3
## libpython:      /usr/local/opt/python/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.7/lib/python3.7/config-3.7m-darwin/libpython3.7.dylib
## pythonhome:     /usr/local/opt/python/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.7:/usr/local/opt/python/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.7
## version:        3.7.2 (default, Feb 12 2019, 08:16:38)  [Clang 10.0.0 (clang-1000.11.45.5)]
## numpy:          /usr/local/lib/python3.7/site-packages/numpy
## numpy_version:  1.17.0
## 
## NOTE: Python version was forced by RETICULATE_PYTHON
reticulate::source_python("mcvisPy.py")
py_result = mcvisPy(x = X)
class(py_result$mc_pd)
## [1] "pandas.core.frame.DataFrame"       
## [2] "pandas.core.generic.NDFrame"       
## [3] "pandas.core.base.PandasObject"     
## [4] "pandas.core.accessor.DirNamesMixin"
## [5] "pandas.core.base.SelectionMixin"   
## [6] "python.builtin.object"
py_MC = py_result$mc_pd %>% reticulate::py_to_r()
dimnames(py_MC) = dimnames(r_result$MC)
py_t_square = py_result$tor

cheat_result = r_result
cheat_result$MC = as.matrix(py_MC)
cheat_result$t_square = py_t_square

ggplot_mcvis(cheat_result)

library(rbenchmark)
benchmark("r" = {mcvis::mcvis(X = X)},
          "python" ={mcvisPy(x = X)},
          replications = 20)
